45":"1221–1245","1275":"1275","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1346":"1346","1247":"1247","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1256":"1256","1278":"1278","1221":"1221","about 1245":"omkring 1245","1308":"1308","1328":"1328","Dennehill, Kingston, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Denne Hill, Kingston, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Denne, Kingstone, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Kingston, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, England","Kingstone, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1245–1308":"circa 1245–1308","1245–1308":"1245–1308","1247–1279":"1247–1279","1275–1328":"1275–1328","1278–1346":"1278–1346","1308–Male":"1308–Overleden","1217–1256":"1217–1256","1221–1245":"1221–1245","1275":"1275","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1346":"1346","1247":"1247","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1256":"1256","1278":"1278","1221":"1221","about 1245":"circa 1245","1308":"1308","1328":"1328","Dennehill, Kingston, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Denne Hill, Kingston, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Denne, Kingstone, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kingston, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, England","Kingstone, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1245–1308":"about 1245–1308","1245–1308":"1245–1308","1247–1279":"1247–1279","1275–1328":"1275–1328","1278–1346":"1278–1346","1308–Male":"1308–Deceased","1217–1256":"1217–1256","1221–1245":"1221–1245","1275":"1275","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1346":"1346","1247":"1247","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1256":"1256","1278":"1278","1221":"1221","about 1245":"about 1245","1308":"1308","1328":"1328","Dennehill, Kingston, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Denne Hill, Kingston, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Denne, Kingstone, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Kingston, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, England","Kingstone, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Denne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Denn  .","French (mainly northern) and Walloon: probably a variant of <b>Dhenne</b>, a patronymic, with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘of’, from <i>Henne</i>, a pet form of the personal names French <i>Henri</i>, Flemish <i>Hendrik</i> (see   Henry   1). Alternatively, perhaps a variant of <b>Daine</b>, the feminine form of   Dain  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Denn","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Denne  , a habitational name from one or more of the numerous places in Kent and Sussex with names derived from Middle English <i>den</i> ‘woodland swine-pasture’ (Old English <i>denn</i>), such as Denne Manor in Chilham, Denne Hill in Kingston, and Denne Court in Woodnesborough (Kent); Denne Park in Horsham, Denne in Warnham, and Dann's Farm in Willingdon (Sussex).","English: possibly from a pet form of   Denis  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":14,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":45,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter de Denne II was born about 1245, in Kingston, Kent, England, his father, Walter de Denne, was 30 and his mother, Lady Sybella Dennehill, was 25. He married Isabell in 1270, in Kingston, Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. His occupation is listed as high steward of the priory of canterbury  in Kent, England, United Kingdom. He died in 1308, in his hometown, at the age of 64."},"et":{"about 1245–1308":"umbes 1245–1308","1245–1308":"1245–1308","1247–1279":"1247–1279","1275–1328":"1275–1328","1278–1346":"1278–1346","1308–Male":"1308–Surnud","1217–1256":"1217–1256","1221–1245":"1221–1245","1275":"1275","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1346":"1346","1247":"1247","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1256":"1256","1278":"1278","1221":"1221","about 1245":"umbes 1245","1308":"1308","1328":"1328","Dennehill, Kingston, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Denne Hill, Kingston, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Denne, Kingstone, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kingston, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, England","Kingstone, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1245–1308":"noin 1245–1308","1245–1308":"1245–1308","1247–1279":"1247–1279","1275–1328":"1275–1328","1278–1346":"1278–1346","1308–Male":"1308–Kuollut","1217–1256":"1217–1256","1221–1245":"1221–1245","1275":"1275","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1346":"1346","1247":"1247","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1256":"1256","1278":"1278","1221":"1221","about 1245":"noin 1245","1308":"1308","1328":"1328","Dennehill, Kingston, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Denne Hill, Kingston, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Denne, Kingstone, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kingston, Kent, 